  "prompt": "Does it cost Starbucks more for the cup their coffee goes in, or the actual coffee itself?",
  "response": "The cost of the cup and the actual coffee in a Starbucks drink can vary significantly depending on several factors, such as the type of coffee, the size of the drink, and the material of the cup. However, in most cases, **the actual coffee itself is cheaper for Starbucks than the cup**.\n\nHere\u2019s a breakdown:\n\n### Cost of the Coffee:\n- Starbucks uses a variety of coffee beans, but even premium beans are relatively inexpensive when purchased in bulk. The cost of the coffee grounds or beans used in a single drink is typically **a fraction of a dollar** (e.g., $0.10 to $0.25 per serving, depending on the type of coffee).\n\n### Cost of the Cup:\n- Starbucks cups are more expensive than the coffee they contain. A standard **paper cup** with a lid in the U.S. can cost Starbucks **$0.10 to $0.25 per cup**, depending on the size and material. For example:\n  - Hot cups (paper) are cheaper, around $0.10 to $0.15.\n  - Cold cups (plastic) are slightly more expensive, around $0.20 to $0.25.\n  - Specialty cups (e.g., reusable or seasonal designs) can cost even more.\n\n### Other Costs:\n- Additional expenses, like labor, milk, flavorings, and syrups, also contribute to the total cost of a drink, but the cup often remains one of the most significant non-labor costs.\n\n### Why the Cup Costs More:\n- The cup is a manufactured product that involves raw materials, production, and transportation costs, whereas coffee beans are a commodity purchased in bulk and roasted in-house or by suppliers.\n\n### Conclusion:\nFor most Starbucks drinks, **the cup costs more than the coffee itself**. This is why Starbucks encourages customers to bring their own reusable cups with discounts or rewards\u2014it helps reduce their costs while promoting sustainability.",
